TY  - JOUR
AU  - Bruno, Michael
AU  - Sachs, Jeffrey
T1  - Input Price Shocks and the Slowdown in Economic Growth: The Case of U.K. Manufacturing
PY  - 1982
Y1  - 1982/12/01
DO  - 10.2307/2297185
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 49
IS  - 5
SP  - 679
EP  - 705
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - This paper provides a theoretical and empirical analysis of the effects of input price shocks on economic growth, with a focus on United Kingdom manufacturing in the 1970s. The theoretical model predicts a discrete decline in output and productivity after an input price rise, and a longer-run slowdown in productivity growth, real wage growth, and capital accumulation. These features characterize the United Kingdom and most other OECD economies after 1973. The empirical results confirm the important role of input prices in recent U.K. adjustment, but also point to an important role for other supply and demand factors.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/2297185
ER  - 



